An American-style capitalism of favoritism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury Department and its IMF allies blamed the problems in that region on crony capitalism, a lack of transparency, and an inefficient government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to bring in American entrepreneurs to teach them how to manage their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed more rapidly than any other region—with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be without fault to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting tricks and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to gain influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism-based capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, is alleged to have tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards-setting body attempted to clean up the accounting of executive bonus-related business dealings.
It is partly thanks to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent has been hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin veil for the benefit of established businesses: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of favoritism-based capitalism.
My interpretation is different: this demonstrates the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to focus on Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was revealed.
Contributions to campaigns were not merely a matter of public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this endeavor.
Some relating to politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the necessity of more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests capable of actually buying elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would confirm the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons focus on economics, more specifically on the economics of information.
For markets to function, for appropriate signals to be provided that aim to allocate resources efficiently, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as positive a picture as possible.
Accounting controls are intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will watch the watchers?
Who will control the account controllers?
We rely heavily on motivation.
The auditors wish to maintain their reputation.
However, the relationship between advisory and audit practices gives rise to other distorted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unrecognized hero of the debacle.
But the accounting control firms and their corporate clients - which is no surprise, given the cabal that has developed - strongly opposed his proposal to separate advisory services from accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood - and what Enron's collapse so clearly demonstrated - is that motivations are important, but that unimpeded markets cannot by themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide incentives for the creation of wealth; they can provide incentives for the kind of deals that Enron was engaged in.
The new economy—and its complex new financial instruments—highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to obscure.
Rather than facing problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will claim that Enron is an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors state that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same way.
They are right - and that's exactly the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received sufficiently reflects a company's economic situation.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, and with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors currently have no possibility of being offered these guarantees.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world have nothing to say about the phenomenon of the "revolving door."
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new sites of abuse are created repeatedly — take, for example, the American repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge to be met is to achieve the right balance.
